\fs32 \cf2 Fixing the "App is damaged" error on macOS
\fs24 \cf0 \

\fs32 \cf2 If you see the message: 
\f2\i "HCalculator.app is damaged and can't be opened"
\f1\i0  when trying to run the program on a Mac, don't worry. The file is not actually broken. This is a standard macOS security feature (Gatekeeper) that quarantines apps downloaded via a web browser.
\fs24 \cf0 \

\fs32 \cf2 To unblock the app, follow these quick steps:
\fs24 \cf0 \
\pard\tqr\tx680\tx760\li760\fi-560\slleading120\sa120\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs28 \cf2 	1.	
\f1\fs32 Open the 
\f0\b Terminal
\f1\b0  application (press 
\f4 Cmd + Space
\f1 , type "Terminal", and press Enter).
\fs24 \cf0 \

\f3\fs28 \cf2 	2.	
\f1\fs32 In the Terminal window, type the following command 
\f0\b (make sure to add a space at the very end!)
\f1\b0 :\

\f4 xattr -cr 
\f1\fs24 \cf0 \

\f3\fs28 \cf2 	3.	
\f1\fs32 Locate the extracted 
\f0\b HCalculator.app
\f1\b0  in your Finder (e.g., in the Downloads folder).
\fs24 \cf0 \

\f3\fs28 \cf2 	4.	
\f1\fs32 Drag and drop the app icon into the Terminal window (the file path will automatically be added after the space).
\fs24 \cf0 \

\f3\fs28 \cf2 	5.	
\f1\fs32 Press 
\f0\b Enter
\f1\b0 . (The terminal will not display any confirmation message, this is normal).
\fs24 \cf0 \

\f3\fs28 \cf2 	6.	
\f1\fs32 Double-click HCalculator to run it again.
\fs24 \cf0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\slleading120\sb340\sa120\partightenfactor0

